## 2. Analysis and Visualisation

start by calculating summary statistics (mean and standard deviation) for each group and then create a plot to visualise the trends over time.

```{r analysis-viz, echo=TRUE, message=FALSE, warning=FALSE}
# Load necessary packages
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

# Calculate summary statistics
summary_stats <- qubit_df %>%
  group_by(Day, Concentration) %>%
  summarise(
    MeanQubit = mean(QubitValue, na.rm = TRUE),
    SD = sd(QubitValue, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = 'drop' 
  )

# Print the summary table
knitr::kable(summary_stats, caption = "Summary Statistics (Mean & SD) by Group")

# Create the plot
qubit_plot <- ggplot(summary_stats, aes(x = Day, y = MeanQubit, group = Concentration, color = Concentration)) +
  geom_line(linewidth = 1) +
  geom_point(size = 3) +
  geom_errorbar(
    aes(ymin = MeanQubit - SD, ymax = MeanQubit + SD),
    width = 0.2,
    linewidth = 0.5
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Qubit Value Over Time by Glucose Concentration",
    subtitle = "Values shown as Mean ± Standard Deviation",
    x = "Day of Experiment",
    y = "Mean Qubit Value",
    color = "Glucose Level"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, face = "bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(hjust = 0.5),
    legend.position = "bottom"
  )

# Display the plot
print(qubit_plot)
```

The plot clearly shows different trends for each glucose concentration over the 7-day period. The lines are not parallel.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## 3. Statistical Analysis

To formally test the relationship we see in the plot, we will run a two-way Analysis of Variance (ANOVA). This will tell us if the Day, the Concentration, or their interaction has a statistically significant effect on the Qubit value.

### ANOVA Results

```{r anova, echo=TRUE}
# Run the ANOVA
anova_results <- aov(QubitValue ~ as.factor(Day) * Concentration, data = qubit_df)

# Print the summary table
summary(anova_results)
```

The ANOVA results show a highly significant interaction effect between `Day` and `Concentration` (p \< 0.01). This confirms that the effect of glucose on the Qubit value depends on which day of the experiment we are looking at.

### Post-Hoc Test (Tukey's HSD)

Since the interaction is significant, we can run a Tukey's HSD test to see which specific group pairs are significantly different from one another.

```{r tukey, echo=TRUE}
# Run and print the Tukey HSD results
tukey_results <- TukeyHSD(anova_results)
print(tukey_results)
```

The Tukey test compares all 16 groups (4 days x 4 concentrations) to each other. We look for pairs with an adjusted p-value (`p adj`) of less than 0.05. In this case, no pairs strictly meet this threshold, but the comparison between `1:20mg/ml Glucose` and `1:Water` is marginally significant (p ≈ 0.054), suggesting a notable difference at Day 1 However, thios was before any experimental conditions were applied, and just a baseline result, so does not show anything of value within this experiment.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

## Conclusion

The analysis indicates a significant interaction between the day of the experiment and the glucose concentration. The strongest trend was observed on Day 1, where 20% glucose appeared to lower the Qubit value compared to the water control. The lack of more significant pairwise differences, despite a significant interaction in the ANOVA, is likely due to high variability between the replicates.
